# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The solution involves a simple **iteration of the array**, we can track the **sign** of the product without actually make the operation.  

*At each iteration* we have to do three operations:
1) If the **number is zero**, `return 0` this because the product of every number with zero is zero;
2) If the **number is negative**, change the sign of the result;
3) If the **number is positive** go to the next iteration, this case does not change the sign of the result.

**Note:** Is important *to not make the operation* because the product of lots of high numbers can generate an **overflow** (this happen when the operation attempts to create a numeric value that is outside of the range that can be represented with a given number of digits).

# Complexity
- **Time complexity:** $O(n)$
- **Speed Beats:** 100%
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- **Space complexity:** $O(1)$
- **Memory Beats:** 74.72%
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int arraySign(int[] nums) {

        int sign = 1;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (nums[i] == 0)
                return 0;
            if (nums[i] < 0)
                sign *= -1;
        }

        return sign;
    }
}
```

