# Intuition
Initial thoughts were to approach as described: find the product and validate. 

# Approach
Realised after writing a solution with initial thoughts that could actually be simplified by checking/validating based on context resulting in expected products. E.g. if `0` exists then product will always be `0` or if there's an odd number of negative integers then it'll alaways end up at 0.

After running a basic comparison of the two approaches it appeared that checking the underlying contexts was faster on larger arrays than using a reducer to find the product. After this I simplified the function down to a one liner.

# Code
```
function arraySign(nums: number[]): number {
    return nums.includes(0) ? 0 : !!(nums.filter((n) => n < 0).length % 2) ? -1 : 1;
};
```

