solutions.content:
I am seeing a lot of solutions using `int` to store the product, or `int` to keep track of the sign by performing multiplication. 

There is a much more concise way -- use a `bool`. Start with a boolean `sign` set to `false`. When we come across a number that is negative, negate `sign`. Once we've passed through every element of the array, just check if `sign` is `true`. If it is, return `-1`, else return `1`. 

Oh, also, we know that any number multiplied by `0` is just going to be `0`, so if at any point we encounter a `0` in our traversal, we can just return `0` right away and be done. 

```
class Solution {

    // Time complexity: O(N)
    // Space complexity: O(1)
    public int arraySign(int[] nums) {

        boolean sign = false; 

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if(nums[i] == 0) // If any number is 0, return 0, right away. 
                return 0; 
            if(nums[i] < 0)
                sign = !sign; 
        }

        return (sign) ? -1 : 1; 


    }
}
```

