At first problem seems to be simple but circular sitting arrangement makes it a bit complex.

Take a look to the given example:
**Tricky part** is to handle the ignoring part that once the number/node is removed how will our code come to know that it is removed from the game. 


![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/813244c8-3213-4f8c-b76e-a1a31d84500c_1666285853.7795105.png)

If you draw all values of n from 1 to 5 with k = 2 to **understand the pattern** to be used for recursion 
```
solve(n, k) depends upon previous step, i.e. solve(n - 1, k), 
solve(n, k) = (solve(n - 1, k) + k) but what if it result in value greater than n? Then if it result in greater value then we will use mod of n with it 

n = 1, k = 2 --> winner = 1
	solve(1, 2) = (0 + 2) % 1 = 0

n = 2, k = 2 --> winner = 1
	solve(2, 2) --> (solve(1, 2) + k) % n = (1 + 2) % 2 = 1 

n = 3, k = 2 --> winner = 3
	solve(3, 2) --> (solve(2, 2) + k) % n = (1 + 2) = 3

n = 4, k = 2 --> winner = 1
	solve(4, 2) --> (solve(3, 2) + k) % n = (3 + 2) % 4 = 1

n = 5, k = 2 --> winner = 3
	solve(5, 2) --> (solve(4, 2) + k) % n = (1 + 2) = 3

```
Code
