# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
    We can represent the circle using a queue of integers, where each integer corresponds to a person in the circle.

    To simulate the elimination process, we can repeatedly remove the k-th person from the front of the queue and add them to the back of the queue until only one person is left.

    Finally, we return the remaining person as the winner. Since the queue is 0-indexed, we need to add 1 to the result before returning it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
    1. Create a queue and add all the elements from 1 to n to the queue
    2. Start a loop until there is only one element remaining in the queue.
    3. In each iteration, remove k-1 elements from the front of the queue and add them to the rear of the queue.
    4. Remove the kth element from the front of the queue.
    5. Repeat steps 3-4 until only one element remains in the queue.
    6. The remaining element is the winner.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n*k)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findTheWinner(int n, int k) {
        vector<int> nums(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            nums[i] = i + 1;
        }

        int index = 0;
        while (n > 1) {
            // Move k steps in the linked list
            index = (index + k - 1) % n;
            // Remove the node at the current index
            nums.erase(nums.begin() + index);
            n--;
        }

        return nums[0];

    }
};
```

