# 
# So before I explain my intutuion to you guys let's look over the complexities
# 
# Time Complexity - O(n) 
# Space Complexity - O(3*n) --> O(n)
# So I sacrifice the space complexity for the time complexity I will tell you reason why

# Intution - 
# Problem - 
So at any position let's suppose frog is at lan 2 and at next point their is obstacle in the lan to avoid collision I have two choices to make that is I can go to Lan1 or Lan3
Now question comes in my mind how would i select which lane should I move when i know next point in the current lan leads to collision.. 
If I know which lan to move optimally than I can reduce the side jumps and can reach to destination with the minimum side jumps.

# To answer the question comes in my mind of choosing the optimal lan 

So I know that whether frog will collide in its next jump or not
If frog going to collide in the next jum than i have to change the lan

To appropriately select which lan i need to know at current point which lan is most far away from the obstacles in their lan

So to know how far is the obstacle from the current point we can use three arrays for each lan.
I know not good to use the three lan but I don't get any other way to know the furthest distance obstacle from the current point

So I created three array  **Lan1,Lan2,Lan3**
Lan1 tells me at current point farthest obstacle and similarly other for their respective Lan

# Let's go through the example to easily understand my intution - 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/64d58173-5bd2-4709-8b04-9e554fde25cb_1620324981.0937715.png)


![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/72de722c-07c4-4e2d-927f-f1c0279c683b_1620324924.2989788.png)

So let's build Lan1
 We have 4 points we start from the end 

#  At point 4
We know their never be the obstacle so we will give **-1**  
# lan1[4] = -1

# At point 3
Now obstacle[3] = 3 so their is no obstacle at point 3 and from lan1[4] = -1 we know that after point 3 also their is no obstacle so we can have **lan1[3] = -1** because we don't have any obstacles after point 3(including the point 3)

# At point 2
obstacles[2] = 2 so still no obstacle at lan1 and also at point 2 lan2[2] = -1 so we don't have any obstacles after the point 2(including the point 2)
# lan1[2] = -1

# At point 1

Now obstacles[1] = 1 so we encounter the obstacle so find what is the distance of the point 1 from the obstacle in the lan1 
Distance is = 1 - 1 = 0 because it is present in the current point so 
# Now we will assign the lan1[1] = 0

# At point 0

obstacles[0] = 0 which mean no obstacles is present in any lan but in lan1 we know that lan1[1] = 0 which means we have the obstacle after point 0 so we need the distance of point 0 from the obstacle

# Distance = lan[1] + 1 = 0 + 1 = 1

because we are just one point away from the point 1 so that means if point 1 is 0 distance far away from the obstacle than point 0 will be the 1 distance away

