solutions.content:
### Why greedy method works?
Look at example 3:
At index 0, frog can **side jump** to lane 1 or lane 3. 
For the case **side jump**  to lane 1, frog  need to go back to lane 3 at index 1 because of  obstacles[2].

We can find that **two cases have *the same status* at index 1**, but the case side jump to lane 1 costs **two** side jump.
So, we can claim the case jump to lane 1 **will never be better than** another case, in any situation.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2184a8a0-3bcd-479c-bb7e-9588e60368c6_1653395982.937031.png)



### But ... How to keep track of two cases? 
### The answer is Quantum Frogs!!

1. When frog side jump, frog **split**.
2. We can use **3 bits** ( lane1 to lane3 ) to record if the quantum frog alive in that lane.
3. When quantum frog meet obstacles, it dies.
4. When all quantum frogs die, means a side jump. 
And quantum frogs appear in other two lanes, excepting obstacle exist at this index.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1020876b-366b-4543-a9cd-d755ec4757b6_1653399540.528078.png)


```
class Solution {
public:
    int minSideJumps(vector<int>& obstacles) {
        int cnt = 0;
        // 3 bits status
        // 000
        // 001
        // 010
        // 011
        // 100
        // 101
        // 110
        // 111
        // turn left 90'
        int status = 2;
        for(int i = 0; i < obstacles.size()-1; i++){
            if(obstacles[i+1] == 2 && (status & (1<<1)) ){
                status -= 2;
                if(status == 0){
                    cnt++;
                    status = 5;
                    // has obstacle on i
                    if(obstacles[i] > 0){
                        status -= (1<<(obstacles[i]-1));
                    }
                }
            }
            else if(obstacles[i+1] == 3 && (status & (1<<2)) ){
                status -= 4;
                if(status == 0){
                    cnt++;
                    status = 3;
                    // has obstacle on i
                    if(obstacles[i] > 0){
                        status -= (1<<(obstacles[i]-1));
                    }
                }
            }
            else if(obstacles[i+1] == 1 && (status & 1) ){
                status -= 1;
                if(status == 0){
                    cnt++;
                    status = 6;
                    // has obstacle on i
                    if(obstacles[i] > 0){
                        status -= (1<<(obstacles[i]-1));
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};
```
