solutions.content:
This problem can be easily solved by simple recursion

Every time the frog has 2 options :
1. move ahead with current lane if no obstacles
       for this no side jump is required.

2. jump to one of the other lane (if no obstacles in the jumping lane)
        for this 1 side jump is required.

Just add memoisation to improve on time complexity
that is save the min side jump if from already visited the index, and reuse the min side jump, if frog gets to revisit same index
```
class Solution {

        public int minSideJumps(int[] obstacle) {
            int n = obstacle.length;
            memory = new Integer[n][4];
            // start with lane = 2, as given in question
            return minSideJumps(obstacle, 0, 2);
        }

        Integer memory[][];

        // return the minimum side jump required to reach enc
        int minSideJumps(int[] obstacle, int i, int curr_lane) {
            //base case: if reached the end position than return 0 (as 0 steps required to reach end)
            if (i == obstacle.length - 1) {
                return 0;
            }

            // if we already have calculated min ans for this position, return simply return ans
            if (memory[i][curr_lane] != null)
                return memory[i][curr_lane];

            // initialise with max value
            int min = 100000000;
            // loop for all the possible lanes to jump(here lane can be: 1, 2, or 3)
            for (int lane = 1; lane <= 3; lane++) {

                // if frog is already in the current lane, and their is no obstacle move ahead( 0 jumps required here)
                if (curr_lane == lane && obstacle[i + 1] != curr_lane) {
                    min = Math.min(minSideJumps(obstacle, i + 1, curr_lane), min);
                }
                // if frog is at different lane, and their is no obstacle in this lane, then jump to this lane(1 jump required here)
                else if (obstacle[i] != lane && obstacle[i + 1] != lane) {
                    min = Math.min(1 + minSideJumps(obstacle, i + 1, lane), min);
                }
            }

            // save the result for this index in memory
            memory[i][curr_lane] = min;

            // return the minium jumps required from this index = i to reach end
            return min;

        }

    }

```

