## Similar problems
This problem is a variant of
- [295. Find Median from Data Stream](https://leetcode.com/problems/find-median-from-data-stream/)
- [480. Sliding Window Median](https://leetcode.com/problems/sliding-window-median/)

And I strongly suggest you read [this post](https://leetcode.com/problems/sliding-window-median/discuss/96346/), which shows an elegant way to rebalance between disjoint sorted sets.

## Intuition

Let's get back to this problem. We're asked to maintain the last `m` elements of a stream, while return its average excluding top `k` and bottom `k` elements. It's easy to infer that some kind of sorted set data structure should be used, and logarithmic maintenance time is required.

### Difficulties

The major difficulties include
1. How to maintain a dynamic sorted set in the first place
2. How to distinguish the top `k` and bottom `k` elements from the candidates for MK average

For 1, C++ users are lucky since there is built-in multiset. However, it's not difficult to implement one in Java. The key is to differentiate between elements with the same value, which can be done using a logical counter incrementing by 1, and this assigned unique identifier can be stored with the value. Several lines of code should suffice to define such a class and corresponding comparator (or alternatively the `Comparable` interface).

For 2, similar to the aforementioned problems, we can use multiple disjoint dynamic sorted sets to distinguish between and maintain subsets of a population. In particular, a top `k` set, a bottom `k` set and a window of candidates for evaluation of MK average should be identified in this problem. Thus 3 multisets are needed. In addition, we should be able to remove expired elements, which can be done by recording the entry order of elements with a single queue.

###  Invariant Maintenance

The most complicated part is maintain the invariant that
> Top `k` set and bottom `k` set contain the corresponding top or bottom `k` elements, while the remaining set contains the `m - 2k` elements left.

Again, I would recommend you reading the post above to learn about the intuition to rebalance between multiple sorted sets. The most important part is to define a **balancing operation**.

## Implementation

```java
class MKAverage {
    static class Element {
        int id;
        int val;

        Element(int id, int val) {
            this.id = id;
            this.val = val;
        }
    }

    int m;
    int k;
    int size = 0;
    int sum = 0;
    Comparator<Element> cmp = Comparator.<Element>comparingInt(e -> e.val).thenComparingInt(e -> e.id);
    TreeSet<Element> window = new TreeSet<>(cmp);
    TreeSet<Element> topK = new TreeSet<>(cmp);
    TreeSet<Element> bottomK = new TreeSet<>(cmp);
    Queue<Element> queue = new ArrayDeque<Element>();

    public MKAverage(int m, int k) {
        this.m = m;
        this.k = k;
    }

    public void addElement(int num) {
        var element = new Element(size++, num);
        queue.offer(element);
        window.add(element);
        sum += num;

        if (size == m) {
            while (window.size() > m - 2 * k) {
                balance();
            }
        } else if (size > m) {
            if (window.last().val > topK.first().val) {
                move(window, topK);
            } else {
                move(window, bottomK);
            }  
            var toRemove = queue.poll();
            topK.remove(toRemove);
            bottomK.remove(toRemove);
            if (window.remove(toRemove)) {
                sum -= toRemove.val;
            }
            balance();
        }
    }

    private void move(TreeSet<Element> from, TreeSet<Element> to) {
        var element = (from == topK || to == bottomK) ? from.pollFirst() : from.pollLast();
        to.add(element);
        sum += to == window ? element.val : -element.val;
    }

    private void balance() {
        if (topK.size() > k) {
            move(topK, window);
        } else if (bottomK.size() > k) {
            move(bottomK, window);
        }

        if (topK.size() < k) {
            move(window, topK);
        } else if (bottomK.size() < k) {
            move(window, bottomK);
        }
    }

    public int calculateMKAverage() {
        return size < m ? -1 : sum / (m - 2 * k);
    }
}
```

